deck_excerpt: THE 8 TIME YCS WINNING STRATEGY - SNAKE EYES!
deck_description:
Don't mind me, just posting my personal try hard Locals Snake-Eye decklist! Snake-Eyes has won the last 8 YCS, and a lot of duelists are absolutely bored and burnt out (pun intended lol) of this fire-centric meta that Ms. Diabellestarr has been dominating. Can't wait until this stale tier 1 deck is finally phased out for something new! Until then... It's good to learn what the best deck of the format does.

The Snake-Eyes engine is straightforward enough - everybody and their mom knows what the cards do and what the optimal combos are by this point. The staples are included specifically to hardcounter the handtrap heavy meta of the current TCG format - hence the Crossout Desginators along with it's banish targets. The sidedeck is full of cards that metagame certain strategies.

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Lunchbox Drafting

Designed for 2 Players.

Based on the idea of a lunchbox with 6 copies of each card in it. An IRL Lunchbox would have 360 cards.

Generally Lunchboxes have a clear 2 Player theme ie Spellcasters vs Fiends, Amazonness vs Harpie, Warrior Zombie Onslaught, etc. 

Players quickly assembled their decks from the pre-built lunchbox card pool before dueling. 

60 Cards

18 Effect Monsters

12 Normal Monsters

18 Spells

14 Traps

Extra deck monsters are not included in the 60 card total.

Some lunchbox drafts use a single field spell for theming, in this case the duel starts with the field spell active.

deck_excerpt: Turbo out Chaos Archfiend and swing for game!
deck_description:
This is an Archfiend build that uses a small Fiendsmith package to boost its consistency, and uses the likes of Weiss, Lightsworn Archfiend and Archfiend Palabyrinth to summon Chaos Archfiend.

Example combos:

Bone Archfiend + Heiress/Palabyrinth = Chaos Archfiend (Bone send Vision, Vision search Crimson, Crimson add Vision, summon Vision, link into Muckraker, revive Bone, send Heiress, search Palabyrinth, Palabyrinth target Muckraker, summon Weiss, synchro)

As does Tour Guide + Heiress/Palabyrinth (same as above but Rhino Warrior off Tour Guide to send Bone to revive off Muckraker)

Bone Archfiend + Fiendsmith also = Chaos Archfiend because you can dump Weiss and then revive it off Lacrimosa

Bone by itself = Soul of Rage (Bone send Vision, Vision search Crimson, Crimson add Vision, summon Vision, link into Yama, search Aruha, pop Crimson, link into Rage)

I'll come back and edit this to include a more comprehensive breakdown, but for now feel free to copy the deck and have a play. Example games all in the video.

Koa'ki Meiru Drago I rarely sided in, and it never came up.

deck_description: ygoprodeck.com
Trains / Railway deck

Dark World Yubel Control Deck

This deck focuses on utilizing the "Dark World" archetype to control the flow of the duel and summon powerful monsters like Yubel and Grapha. Here's a breakdown of its core strategies:

  • Yubel Powerhouse: The deck utilizes multiple forms of Yubel, including "Yubel - Terror Incarnate" for swarming and "Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare" for powerful removal. "Spirit of Yubel" provides additional resources and graveyard manipulation.
  • Dark World Engine: "Reign-Beaux," "Grapha," "Sillva," and "Snoww" form the core of the Dark World engine, searching each other and generating advantage.
  • Discard Fodder and Advantage: Cards like "Genta," "Broww," and "Gruesome Grave Squirmer" provide discard fodder for Dark World effects while offering benefits like searching or graveyard setup. "Trade-In" and "Card Destruction" further fuel the discard strategy, while "Samsara D Lotus" and "Nightmare Pain" reward you for discarding.
  • Search and Consistency: "Dark World Accession," "Dark World Archives," and "The Gates of Dark World" search for key Dark World cards, ensuring you have the tools you need.
  • Control Elements: "Skill Drain" shuts down your opponent's monster effects, while "Eternal Favorite" protects your Yubel monsters. "Nightmare Throne" offers additional field control with its effect negation.
  • Extra Deck Toolbox: The Extra Deck offers a variety of options depending on the situation. "Yubel - The Loving Defender Forever" and "Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World" capitalize on the Dark World strategy. "Number 97: Draglubion" and "The Zombie Vampire" provide removal, while "Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy" offers card advantage. The deck also features generic Rank 4 and Link monsters for various needs.

This deck prioritizes controlling the duel through targeted removal, hand disruption with Dark World effects, and strong monsters like Yubel. It utilizes its discard strategy to gain advantage and access powerful effects. Be aware that "Card Destruction" can be risky, so use it strategically.

Ele são focados em condições de vitória alternativa. Ele está relacionado ao arquétipo "Forbidden One".

Enquanto muitas pessoas se referem aos cards "Forbidden One" como cards "Exodia", apenas "Exodia the Forbidden One" (a cabeça) é parte deste arquétipo.

O card principal, "Exodia the Forbidden One", é um dos cinco primeiros Monstros de Efeito a serem lançados e o primeiro card a ter uma condição de vitória alternativa.

Notavelmente, "Exodia the Forbidden One" e os outros cards "Forbidden One" foram os únicos monstros já mencionados especificamente no manual de regras (exceto como um exemplo), devido à "Exodia the Forbidden One" ser o único card com uma condição de vitória alternativa naquele momento.

Tried out the new ice barrier support in EDOPro and I ended up liking it a lot! Here's the list I cooked up after testing for a bit. The main goal is to summon Lancea and hopefully another synchro 10 to protect the field (I preferred Gymir Aegerine). Revealer is your ideal starter - the mirror mage is mostly used with discard/foolish burial, and Georgius is your way to bring out Wayne for Frozen Domain, although his other searches aren't bad in case you drew it. Once Lancea is on the field, your targets for it are Raiho and Defender. I usually search Raiho first to force the opponent to go minus, and defender second to deny combat. 

Generic interruptions can be swapped out as desired. I personally have phantazmay in the side deck for Snake-eye or any other link matchups, ghost ogre to deal with Tenpai, dark ruler + evenly for going second, and synchro zone for going first.

 

I didn't do any specific ratio testing - I have a hunch that mirror magic master could be playable at 1 copy. Water charmer could potentially be swapped out for Almiraj to get mirror master into the grave (though I never bricked on him in testing). Little Knight probably has its use but I did not include her to save my wallet. In cases where you're playing Little Knight, be wary of waterlocking yourself.

deck_description: Agustin Da Silva 23vo NACIONAL ARGENTINA 2024
Just for fun
Yelough - Fusion Gate
Yelough - Chaos Turbo

I think that Fiendsmith as an archetype is pretty cool. I know that currently, some people aren’t seeing it more than a 1-card combo without using your Normal Summon that gets you a D/D/D Wave High King Caesar onto your field for 2 Solemn Warning effects. But to me, while I still think that is very powerful, it either just serves to protect you against Nibiru or it just adds on 2 more interruptions on a board that already had enough interaction to run your opponent out of resources without the inclusion of Caesar. Fiendsmith has 1 Level 9 monster in Fiendsmith Dies Irae who is a Level 9 LIGHT Fiend Fusion Monster that requires The Fiendsmith and 2 LIGHT Fiends as Fusion Material. It can Quick Effect negate the effects of face-up cards on the field until the end of the turn up to the total Link Rating of the Link Monsters equipped to it and if it is sent to the GY, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend from your GY into the Deck or Extra Deck to target and send a card on the field to the GY. Putting together Fiendsmith and Prediction Princess seemed incredibly weird to me even though I’ve created worse variants like Code Talker Prediction Princess. On one hand, you could just play the Fiendsmith engine to get to Dies Irae and have no other usage for the engine outside of that. On the other hand, you could actually play Fiendsmith Prediction Princess, using the Fiendsmith cards for more than just getting to a Level 9. And to be fair, there is a lot that I want to do with Fiendsmith because Prediction Princess gives you access to cards like Mereologic Aggregator and Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton who have some unique interactions with the Fiendsmith Fusion and Link Monsters. And I think that I have managed to make that work with this Decklist here. So, for our combo, we need The Fiendsmith, World Legacy Monstrosity, and any way to get another monster onto our field like a Normal Summon or a free Summon. Let’s say that will be us Normal Summoning Ash Blossom. We are going through a similar combo that you may have already seen people using to go from 1 The Fiendsmith into Wave High King Caesar, but we are going to be tweaking it at the end to transition us into Dies Irae instead. Activate The Fiendsmith to discard itself to search Fiendsmith Sanctus. Activate Fiendsmith Sanctus to Summon a Fiendsmith Token. Link that Token into Fiendsmith Requiem. Requiem Tributes itself to Special Summon another The Fiendsmith from Deck. Activate your other The Fiendsmith in GY to shuffle Fiendsmith Requiem from GY into Extra Deck to Special Summon itself from GY. Link your 2 The Fiendsmiths into Moon of the Closed Sky. Normal Summon Ash Blossom and then Link Ash and Moon of the Closed Sky into Fiendsmith Sequentia. Sequentia activates its effect to shuffle both The Fiendsmiths and Moon of the Closed Sky into Deck/Extra Deck to Fusion Summon Fiendsmith Dies Irae. Activate Monstrosity targeting Dies Irae to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Dies Irae into Mereologic Aggregator to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck. And it is the same song and dance from there on. While it was weird to me at first, looking at it now, Fiendsmith is not too bad with Prediction Princess. On one hand, if you do draw Monstrosity, you are able to go through the Aggregator line to get your Ritual components. On the other, because the Fiendsmith engine is pretty small for all things considered and because it doesn’t require a Normal Summon, you can play Diviner of the Herald to get more Ritual searches from sending Herald of the Arc Light while also playing a decent amount of non-engine. You could also decide to play things like Pre-Preparation of Rites and Prediction Ritual to have more access to your Ritual stuff if you value that over more non-engine. And of course, don’t forget that you can still do Fiendsmith plays to get to Wave High King Caesar to either protect yourself against Nibiru or to use as interruption when you draw the stuff you need for your Prediction Princess plays already. This Deck doesn’t show off the potential of Fiendsmith Prediction Princess as much as it displays the power of Fiendsmith as a 1-card combo enabler. While I still think that Fiendsmith Prediction Princess is good, it just requires you to make the decision between playing more engine or more non-engine to either see more of your Prediction Princess cards or to have more options for interruption, especially for going second. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. Pot of the Forbidden, on flip, allows you to draw 2 cards, return all Spell/Trap Cards on field to the hand, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card of your choice back into the Deck. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can be sent off of Diviner of the Herald and Summon itself back from GY by Tributing said Diviner. This card is more or less just a Level 9 monster you can access off of Diviner that you can target with Monstrosity to get Deus-X and Pot of the Forbidden from the Deck in a situation where you have Diviner but you don’t have The Fiendsmith. 3 The Fiendsmith. You can discard it to add a Fiendsmith Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand, while it is on field, you can target a Fiendsmith equip card and a monster on the fiend and send both to the GY, and if it is in the Gy, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend monster from your Gy into the Deck/Extra Deck to Special Summon this card. As you would pretty much already know, this card by itself is a 1-card Rank 6 Xyz Monster or it can allow you to go into a Fiendsmith Fusion Monster if you go for Fiendsmith Sequentia. 3 Diviner of the Herald. Because you don’t have a Normal Summon in the Fiendsmith engine, we can play this card to either get a Level 9 on field in Trias Hierarchia or you can use it as your Normal Summonable monster which would then be used for Link Material during your Fiendsmith combo who can also get you a Ritual Spell or Ritual Monster by sending Herald of the Arc Light to GY on Summon. And for the rest of the monsters, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Effect Veiler. Again, you could cut any number of these to play more engine pieces in Pre-Preparation of Rites and Prediction Ritual. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Fiendsmith Sanctus and 3 Fiendsmith Tractus. Tractus Special Summons a Fiendsmith Token (Fiend/LIGHT/Level 1/ATK 0/DEF 0) if you control no face-up monsters or if all monsters you control are LIGHT Fiend monsters while also locking you into attacking with Fiends for the rest of the turn. Tractus is the card that you always want to search off of The Fiendsmith. The Token it Summons allows you to Link it off into Fiendsmith Requiem who then Tributes itself to get another The Fiendsmith from Deck onto Field while also putting itself into the GY for your other The Fiendsmith in GY to shuffle back to Special Summon itself, putting 2 Level 6’s onto the field. Even so, this card is not a brick that you want to keep in your Deck at all times. If you draw it, it is completely fine as you can just grab Tractus from Deck with The Fiendsmith. But you just need the 1. Its GY effect is not really relevant as I don’t see us meeting the activation requirements for Sanctus past the start of your Turn 1. Tractus searches a LIGHT Fiend and then makes you discard a card. And you can also banish it from GY to Fusion Summon a Fiendsmith Fusion using monsters from your field. Other than being an incredible card for Fabled, this basically just is 3 more copies of The Fiendsmith which is great. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. And finally, 1 Called By the Grave and 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 2 Fiendsmith Dies Irae. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. On Xyz Summon, it can send a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY and you can target any number of monsters in your GY up to the number of Xyz Materials it has, detach the same number of Xyz Materials, and attach the targets in GY to it as material. Something to note about Aggregator’s first effect is that it can trigger the GY effects of the Fiendsmith Fusion Monsters as they have an effect that activates when sent to GY. Dies Irae shuffles another LIGHT Fiend in GY into Deck/Extra Deck and targets and sends a card on the field to the GY. Fiendsmith Lacrimosa shuffles 1 other LIGHT Fiend in GY into Deck/Extra Deck to inflict 1200 damage to your opponent. It can also send a Fiendsmith Link to allow it to equip itself from GY to a Fiendsmith monster you control, but that is less value than what you can accomplish with Essentially, on a following turn, you can go for another Aggregator to send Dies Irae from Extra Deck to GY and then have the ability to target and send a card on field to GY. But this also works when Aggregator reattaches Dies Irae from GY and is sent to GY as well. The same goes for Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton’s negation effect, but we aren’t playing it for the sake of space. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. Laevateinn tributing itself also sends a Dies Irae it has as material to GY which can also be used to trigger its effect. 1 D/D/D Wave High King Caesar which when a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect is activated that includes an effect that Special Summons a monster, you can detach a material to negate the activation and destroy that card with this effect not being once per turn. I have played with this card in Sharks alongside Xyz Revive Splash in the past, but with the Fiendsmith cards, summoning it in any Deck is a breeze. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Moon of the Closed Sky. This is not necessary as you could just play the second copy of Sequentia instead since we just need a second Link-2 Light Fiend in our Extra Deck. Speaking of, 1 Fiendsmith Sequentia which requires 2 monsters including a LIGHT Fiend as material and during your Mani Phase, you can Fusion Summon a Fiend monster from your Extra Deck by shuffling the materials from your GY into the Deck. Its other effect is not necessary in this Deck. Finally, 1 Fiendsmith Requiem which is a Link-1 that requires a LIGHT Fiend as material and you can Quick Effect tribute it during the Main Phase to Special Summon a Fiendsmith monster from hand or Deck.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 1 Droll & Lock Bird, 3 Crossout Designator, 3 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Insert Bad to the Bone riff
deck_description:
I think that Memento is a really cool Deck. It definitely was rough coming out of Valiant Smashers (at least not as bad as Vaalmonica), but with the support it is has gotten from Phantom Nightmare in Mementotlan Ghattic, from Legacy of Destruction in Mementotlan Twin Dragon, and soon in Infinite Forbidden in Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror, Mementotlan Mystical Sheep, and Mementotlan Fusion, the Deck is now very playable with several 1-card combos that end you on some of the Deck’s more unique plays. And it just so happens that Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror is a Level 9 monster. It is a Level 9 EARTH Illusion Fusion Monster that requires 3 Memento monsters as Fusion Material. On Fusion Summon, it allows you to send 3 Memento cards from your Deck and/or Extra Deck to the GY and you can Quick Effect target an equal number of Memento monsters you control and cards your opponent controls to destroy them. And while this card is in your GY, you can banish it to add a Mementomictlan from your Deck to your hand. This card, even though it requires 3 Memento monsters, is actually pretty easy to Summon due to Memento Mystical Sheep and Mementotlan Fusion. Being able to send 3 Memento cards on Summon is actually a very powerful effect considering that you can send cards like Mementotlan Fusion or even another copy of Combined Conqueror to either search for another Memento Spell/Trap or search for Mementomictlan. But it can also be used to get enough Memento names into the GY to Summon Mementoal Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation or to put a Memento Trap into GY to set it during the End Phase with Mementomictlan. Combined Conqueror is also interruption itself which gives it even more purpose. However, because we are combining Memento with Prediction Princess, we run into a couple issues. Memento doesn’t play too well with cards outside of its own archetype. It definitely can, but you want to see Memento names more often than not, so you have to play a large number of them. They also have a lot of cards you don’t necessarily want to draw either, but not hard garnets. So, we have to make a decision between playing a large Memento package to end on Memento cards in addition to our Prediction Princess plays or play the core Memento cards we need to help us transition to Prediction Princess plays. I decided to play the core Memento cards primarily because of the redundancy of playing Memento Cranium Burst in addition to Deus-X Krawler. Why want 5 monster negates when you already have continuous monster negation with Deus-X. Even if we could use Whirlwind Weasel for an alternative Flip option to Deus-X, it is another brick that also requires us to play more unnecessary cards to set up Cranium Burst. This Deck has 2 combos you can do to get to Combined Conqueror. The first requires you to draw Mementotlan Dark Blade which allows us to set up a Combined Creation to potentially bring back Combined Conqueror from GY on our opponent’s turn for at least 2 pops in addition to our Prediction Princess plays. The second requires you to start with Mementotlan Angwitch which gets us straight to Combined Conqueror, transitioning to Prediction Princess plays. It can potentially also get us to Combined Creation, but more often than not, it doesn’t put enough names into rotation. Let’s say we start with Mementotlan Dark Blade. Normal Summon it and use its effect to destroy itself to Summon Angwitch from Deck. Angwitch on Summon adds Mementotlan Tatsunootoshigo from Deck. Tatsunootoshigo activates to Summon itself from hand and then activate its other effect to pop itself to send Mementotlan Mace and another name like Dark Blade or Angwitch to GY. Angwitch’s other effect pops herself to Summon back Mace from GY. Mace uses its effect to pop itself to add Mementotlan Fusion from Deck. Activate Mementotlan Fusion which allows you to Fuse using your GY since a monster in your possession was destroyed this turn. Shuffle Tatsunootoshigo and the second copy of Angwitch or Dark Blade (whichever you sent earlier) from GY into Deck to Fusion Summon Mementotlan Twin Dragon. On Fusion Summon, Twin Dragon pops itself to add Mementotlan Mystical Sheep and another name which can be Combined Creation or another Memento monster from Deck to hand, let’s say you added Combined Creation. Twin Dragon activates in GY as it was destroyed to Summon back any Level 6 or lower Memento name in GY. Activate Mystical Sheep in hand to Special Summon itself since a monster in your possession was destroyed by card effect this turn. On Summon, it Fusion Summons a Memento Fusion Monster using materials from hand or field. Fuse itself, the Memento monster you summoned from GY off of Twin Dragon, and the Combined Creation in your hand into Combined Conqueror into your EMZ. Conqueror activates to send any 3 Memento cards from Deck/Extra Deck to GY (it does not matter). Now, if you have World Legacy Monstrosity in hand, you can target Combined Conqueror with it to get Trias Hierarchia and Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag from Deck and then overlay for Mereologic Aggregator to transition to full Prediction Princess combo. Later, you can shuffle 5 Memento names excluding Combined Conqueror into Deck to Special Summon Combined Creation from GY. You can either use it as Link Material with Aggregator for I:P Masquerena or S:P Little Knight or you can keep it on field to bring back Conqueror during your opponent’s turn for potentially 2 pops. If we started with Angwitch, Normal Summon her, use her to search for Tatsunootoshigo. Tatsunootoshigo Summons itself from hand, popping itself to send Mace and another name from Deck to GY. Angwitch pops herself to Summon back Mace. Mace pops itself to search for Mementotlan Fusion. Mementotlan Fusion shuffles 3 Mementos from GY into Deck to Summon Combined Conqueror. Conqueror can send anything (it does not matter). Then, if you have Monstrosity or Kaku in hand, you can transition to Prediction Princess plays. Overall, I would say that Memento Prediction Princess is neat, but it is not that optimal. Memento having a lot of 1-card combos is really nice, but with Combined Conqueror being EARTH Attribute, it is not the most optimal Level 9 to be using for Prediction Princess. I would much rather play pure Memento. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. Pot of the Forbidden, on flip, allows you to draw 2 cards, return all Spell/Trap Cards on field to the hand, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card of your choice back into the Deck. 1 Trias Hierarchia which goes along with our 3 Diviner of the Herald. It might seem strange to see Diviner being played when we already have other monsters that facilitate an entire combo themselves on Normal Summon like Angwitch and Dark Blade, but Diviner is in this Deck because if you draw Diviner and a Memento name other than Mace, you have full Prediction Princess combo as well. Mementotlan Mace is a Level 1 Fairy monster which means that it can be Summoned off of Diviner after it has been Tributed off of Trias Hierarchia. Mace then destroys itself to search for Mementotlan Fusion which Fusion Summons using Mace in GY and the other Memento name in hand for Twin Dragon who pops itself on Fusion Summon to search for Mystical Sheep and another Memento name. Twin Dragon triggers on destruction to bring back the other Memento name in GY and Mystical Sheep activates to Special Summon itself from hand. Sheep and the two other Memento names on field and in hand Fuse with Sheep’s effect for Combined Conqueror where it and Trias Hierarchia are 2 Level 9’s you can Xyz into Aggregator. Hierarchia also serves as a Level 9 to Summon from Deck when targeting Combined Conqueror on field with Monstrosity. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag. This card can activate to Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ. You can just Special Summon Combined Conqueror into the EMZ and Summon Kaku from hand for 2 Level 9’s on field, and Kaku also serves as a Level 9 to Summon from Deck off of Monstrosity targeting Conqueror. 1 Memento Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation which Must be Special Summoned from hand/GY by shuffling 5 other Memento monsters with different names from hand/GY into the Deck/Extra Deck. And once per turn if your opponent activates a card or effect, you can Special Summon 1 Memento monster from hand or GY. You really do not need to play this card. But it gives you another form of interruption given that you start with Mementotlan Dark Blade as it can Summon back Combined Conqueror if your opponent activates a card or effect. In place of this, you could play the second copy of Mace. 1 Mementotlan Tatsunootoshigo which can Special Summon itself from hand if you do not control any face-up monsters other than Memento monsters. Its other effect allows you to destroy a Memento monster you control for effect and send any number of Memento monsters with different names from your Deck to the GY whose total Levels are less than or equal to the destroyed monster’s original Level. 3 Mementotlan Dark Blade and 3 Mementotlan Angwitch. Dark Blade and discard a Memento card on Summon to target and destroy a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and it can also destroy a memento monster you control for effect to Special Summon a Level 3 or lower Memento monster from Deck. You could use this card as Spell/Trap removal, but it is primarily here to get Angwitch from Deck. Angwitch can add another Memento monster from Deck to hand on Summon and you can target a Level 2 or lower Memento monster in your GY and destroy a Memento monster you control for effect to Summon back the targeted monster. 1 Mementotlan Mystical Sheep which only has 2 relevant effects we are using. If a monster(s) in your possession was destroyed by card effect this turn, you can Special Summon it from your hand. And on Summon, it can Fusion Summon a Memento Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using material from hand or field. This card is nuts in a pure Memento Deck, but here, it is just a way for us to transition from Twin Dragon to Combined Conqueror. 1 Mementotlan Mace which we are only using to pop a Memento monster we control for effect to add a Memento card from Deck to hand. Again, you can decide not to play Combined Creation to play a second Mace if you want. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 2 Mementotlan Fusion which can Fusion Summon any Fusion Monster from Extra Deck using monsters from your hand or field as material including a Memento and if a monster(s) in your possession was destroyed this turn, you can also shuffle Memento monsters from GY into the Deck as material. Also, you can banish it from your GY and destroy a monster you control to add a Memento Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand. This card being able to get out any Fusion Monster is incredible as it gives you the ability to go for Guardian Chimera on your opponent’s turn if you want as it is a Quick-Play Spell Card, and being able to use your hand, field, and GY for material is such a huge boon this card gives to Memento. Furthermore, its effect to search a Memento Spell/Trap can also search another copy of it which means that you can really set-up for a potential Guardian Chimera on your opponent’s turn given that you do your standard combo. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. And finally, 1 Called By the Grave and 3 Triple Tactics Talent. 

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. 1 Guardian Chimera. 2 Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror. 1 Memento Twin Dragon which requires 2 Memento monsters as material and on Fusion Summon, it can pop a Memento monster you control or in hand for effect to search for up to 2 Memento monsters with different names from your Deck, and if it is popped, you can Special Summon a Level 6 or lower Memento monster from your GY. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Lightning Storm, the third Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Evenly Matched.
